/Spring
Inversion of Control vs Dependency Injection?
- DI is implementation of IoC in Spring. Main idea - delegate objects creation of logic classes to container that will manage it(beans)
How to inject specific bean by its name?
- @Qualifier
Why injecting via constructor is recommended way? why better then @Autowired or via setter?
- field can be final and cannot later be changed by mistake,
- object is created ONLY if all dependencies are ready,
- no reflection search
- Spring throws error at startup if there is circular dependency with constructor injection. With setter/field injection, Spring can sometimes "solve" circular dependency using proxy — but this hides real design problem.
Can you inject list of beans, like List<Validator> validators;?
- Yes, spring will automatically find all implementations of Validator interface and inject them in this list.
Cycle dependency, what is it? how to solve it?
- ServiceA has dependency(injected bean field) - ServiceB and ServiceB has dependency to ServiceA.
- Best way - redesign the app to avoid such Cycle dependency
- use ObjectProvider<ServiceB> serviceBProvider; and ServiceB serviceB = serviceBProvider.getObject();
- @Lazy ServiceB serviceB - pring creates proxy first, real bean loaded only when actually used.
- inject via setters or @Autowired // works but hides design problem

